  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a gradient descent?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "Gradient descent is an optimization method used to find the minimum of a function.\n\nIn machine learning, it is commonly used to reduce a model’s error or loss by gradually adjusting the model’s parameters.\n\nThe basic idea:\n\n1. Start with some initial parameter values.\n2. Calculate the gradient, which tells you the direction of steepest increase of the loss function.\n3. Move in the opposite direction of the gradient, because you want to reduce the loss.\n4. Repeat until the loss is low enough or stops improving.\n\nMathematically, an update often looks like:\n\n\\[\n\\theta = \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\theta\\) represents the parameters of the model\n- \\(J(\\theta)\\) is the loss function\n- \\(\\nabla J(\\theta)\\) is the gradient of the loss\n- \\(\\alpha\\) is the learning rate, which controls how big each step is\n\nA simple analogy: imagine you are standing on a hill in the fog and want to get to the lowest point. You feel which direction slopes downward the most and take a small step that way. Repeating this process is like gradient descent.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "Gradient descent is an optimization method used to **find the minimum of a function**.\n\nIn machine learning, that function is usually a **loss function**, which measures how wrong a model’s predictions are. Gradient descent helps adjust the model’s parameters so the loss becomes smaller.\n\nThe basic idea:\n\n1. Start with some initial parameter values.\n2. Calculate the **gradient**, which tells you the direction of steepest increase.\n3. Move in the **opposite direction** of the gradient to reduce the loss.\n4. Repeat until the loss is small or stops improving.\n\nMathematically, the update rule is:\n\n\\[\n\\theta = \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n\n- \\(\\theta\\) = model parameters\n- \\(\\alpha\\) = learning rate\n- \\(\\nabla J(\\theta)\\) = gradient of the loss function\n- \\(J(\\theta)\\) = loss function\n\nThe **learning rate** controls how big each step is. If it is too large, the algorithm may overshoot the minimum. If it is too small, training may be very slow.\n\nA simple analogy: imagine you are standing on a hill in fog and want to get to the lowest point. You feel which direction slopes downward most steeply, take a step that way, and repeat. That is gradient descent.",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"gradient descent\" differ from stochastic gradient descent (SGD)?",
    "How does \"gradient descent\" differ from Newton's method?",
    "How does \"gradient descent\" differ from simulated annealing?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "Gradient descent and stochastic gradient descent (SGD) differ mainly in **how much data they use to compute each update**.\n\n## Gradient Descent\n\nIn standard, or **batch gradient descent**, the model calculates the gradient using the **entire training dataset** before updating the parameters.\n\nUpdate idea:\n\n\\[\n\\theta = \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere the gradient is computed from all training examples.\n\n### Characteristics\n\n- Uses the full dataset for each update\n- More stable and accurate gradient direction\n- Can be slow for large datasets\n- Updates happen less frequently\n\n## Stochastic Gradient Descent\n\nIn **stochastic gradient descent**, the model updates its parameters using **one training example at a time**.\n\nInstead of computing the gradient over the whole dataset, SGD estimates the gradient from a single randomly chosen example.\n\n### Characteristics\n\n- Uses one data point per update\n- Much faster per update\n- Updates are noisier and less stable\n- Can escape shallow local minima or saddle points more easily\n- Often works well for large datasets\n\n## Simple comparison\n\n| Method | Data used per update | Speed per update | Stability |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Gradient Descent | Entire dataset | Slower | More stable |\n| SGD | One example | Faster | Noisier |\n\n## Mini-batch gradient descent\n\nIn practice, people often use **mini-batch gradient descent**, which is between the two.\n\nIt uses a small batch of examples, such as 32, 64, or 128, for each update.\n\n| Method | Data used per update |\n|---|---:|\n| Batch gradient descent | All examples |\n| SGD | 1 example |\n| Mini-batch gradient descent | Small group of examples |\n\nSo, the key difference is:\n\n**Gradient descent uses all training data for each parameter update, while SGD uses one randomly selected training example per update.**",
    "Gradient descent and Newton’s method are both optimization methods, but they differ in **what information they use** and **how they choose each step**.\n\n## Gradient Descent\n\nGradient descent uses the **first derivative**, or gradient, of the function.\n\nIt updates parameters by moving in the direction of steepest decrease:\n\n\\[\n\\theta = \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\theta\\) are the parameters\n- \\(J(\\theta)\\) is the loss function\n- \\(\\nabla J(\\theta)\\) is the gradient\n- \\(\\alpha\\) is the learning rate\n\n### Key idea\n\nGradient descent asks:\n\n> “Which direction decreases the function most steeply?”\n\nIt then takes a step in that direction.\n\n## Newton’s Method\n\nNewton’s method uses both the **first derivative** and the **second derivative**.\n\nFor optimization, the update is:\n\n\\[\n\\theta = \\theta - H^{-1} \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\nabla J(\\theta)\\) is the gradient\n- \\(H\\) is the Hessian matrix, containing second derivatives\n- \\(H^{-1}\\) is the inverse of the Hessian\n\n### Key idea\n\nNewton’s method asks:\n\n> “Using the curvature of the function, where does the minimum appear to be?”\n\nIt uses curvature information to make a more informed step.\n\n## Main differences\n\n| Feature | Gradient Descent | Newton’s Method |\n|---|---|---|\n| Uses gradient? | Yes | Yes |\n| Uses second derivatives? | No | Yes |\n| Needs learning rate? | Usually yes | Often no, though damped versions may use one |\n| Step direction | Steepest downhill direction | Curvature-adjusted direction |\n| Cost per step | Lower | Higher |\n| Convergence near minimum | Usually slower | Often faster |\n| Common in deep learning? | Yes | Less common due to cost |\n\n## Intuition\n\nGradient descent is like walking downhill by only checking the slope under your feet.\n\nNewton’s method is like also knowing the shape of the hill around you, so you can take a smarter step toward the bottom.\n\n## Practical difference\n\nGradient descent is simpler and cheaper, especially for models with many parameters.\n\nNewton’s method can converge in fewer iterations, but computing and inverting the Hessian can be very expensive for large machine learning models.\n\nSo the core difference is:\n\n**Gradient descent uses only slope information, while Newton’s method uses both slope and curvature information.**",
    "Gradient descent and simulated annealing are both optimization methods, but they work in very different ways.\n\n## Gradient Descent\n\nGradient descent uses the **gradient**, or derivative, of a function to decide which direction to move.\n\nIt repeatedly moves in the direction that most quickly decreases the function:\n\n\\[\n\\theta = \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\theta\\) represents the parameters\n- \\(J(\\theta)\\) is the objective or loss function\n- \\(\\nabla J(\\theta)\\) is the gradient\n- \\(\\alpha\\) is the learning rate\n\n### Key idea\n\nGradient descent asks:\n\n> “Which direction is downhill?”\n\nThen it takes a step in that direction.\n\n### Characteristics\n\n- Requires the function to be differentiable, or at least have usable gradients\n- Usually follows a local downhill path\n- Can get stuck in local minima or saddle points\n- Very common in machine learning and deep learning\n- Efficient for large continuous optimization problems\n\n---\n\n## Simulated Annealing\n\nSimulated annealing is a **probabilistic search algorithm** inspired by the physical process of cooling metal.\n\nInstead of always moving downhill, it sometimes accepts worse solutions, especially early in the search. This helps it escape local minima.\n\nThe probability of accepting a worse move decreases over time according to a parameter called the **temperature**.\n\n### Key idea\n\nSimulated annealing asks:\n\n> “Should I try this new solution, even if it is worse, to avoid getting stuck?”\n\nAt high temperature, it explores more freely.  \nAt low temperature, it becomes more conservative.\n\n### Characteristics\n\n- Does not require gradients\n- Can work with non-differentiable, discrete, or noisy objective functions\n- Can escape local minima by accepting worse moves\n- Often slower than gradient-based methods\n- Useful for combinatorial optimization problems, scheduling, routing, and search problems\n\n---\n\n## Main differences\n\n| Feature | Gradient Descent | Simulated Annealing |\n|---|---|---|\n| Uses gradients? | Yes | No |\n| Requires differentiability? | Usually yes | No |\n| Search style | Moves downhill using slope | Randomly explores possible solutions |\n| Can accept worse solutions? | Usually no | Yes |\n| Local minima | Can get stuck | Can escape them |\n| Common use | Machine learning, continuous optimization | Discrete optimization, global search |\n| Speed | Often faster | Often slower |\n| Deterministic? | Often mostly deterministic | Stochastic/random |\n\n---\n\n## Intuition\n\nGradient descent is like walking downhill in the fog by feeling the slope beneath your feet.\n\nSimulated annealing is like exploring a landscape by sometimes walking uphill on purpose, hoping to find a better valley somewhere else.\n\n---\n\n## Practical difference\n\nUse **gradient descent** when the objective function is smooth, differentiable, and you can compute gradients efficiently.\n\nUse **simulated annealing** when gradients are unavailable, the search space is discrete or irregular, or you need a better chance of escaping local minima.\n\nSo the core difference is:\n\n**Gradient descent follows the local slope downhill, while simulated annealing performs a randomized search that can sometimes move uphill to find better global solutions.**"
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"gradient descent\": Gradient descent is a first-order iterative optimization algorithm that minimizes a differentiable function by repeatedly stepping in the direction of the negative gradient at the current point, with step size controlled by a learning rate. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged. I have read the canonical definition of gradient descent.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "Gradient descent usually refers to **batch gradient descent**, while **stochastic gradient descent (SGD)** is a variant that uses random samples to estimate the gradient.\n\n| Aspect | Gradient Descent | Stochastic Gradient Descent |\n|---|---|---|\n| Gradient computation | Uses the **entire dataset** to compute the gradient | Uses **one randomly selected training example** at a time |\n| Update frequency | One update per full pass over the dataset | Updates after each individual example |\n| Accuracy of gradient | More accurate/stable gradient | Noisy approximation of the true gradient |\n| Speed per update | Slower, especially for large datasets | Faster per update |\n| Convergence path | Smoother and more direct | More noisy, may fluctuate |\n| Scalability | Less efficient for very large datasets | Better suited for large-scale machine learning |\n\nIn standard gradient descent, the update is based on the full loss:\n\n\\[\n\\theta = \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nIn SGD, the update uses the loss from a single randomly chosen example:\n\n\\[\n\\theta = \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J_i(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(J_i(\\theta)\\) is the loss for one training example.\n\nSo the main difference is:\n\n**Gradient descent computes the exact gradient using all training data, while SGD estimates the gradient using one randomly chosen data point at a time.**\n\nIn practice, many systems use **mini-batch gradient descent**, which is between the two: it computes the gradient using a small batch of examples rather than the full dataset or just one example.",
    "Gradient descent and Newton’s method are both iterative optimization methods, but they differ mainly in the information they use to choose each step.\n\n| Aspect | Gradient Descent | Newton’s Method |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type of method | First-order optimization method | Second-order optimization method |\n| Uses gradient? | Yes | Yes |\n| Uses Hessian / curvature? | No | Yes |\n| Step direction | Negative gradient direction | Direction adjusted by curvature |\n| Step size | Controlled by learning rate | Often determined by Hessian; may still use damping/line search |\n| Computational cost | Usually cheaper per iteration | More expensive per iteration |\n| Convergence | Often slower, especially near optimum | Often faster near optimum |\n| Practicality in large ML models | Very common | Often too expensive for large models |\n\nGradient descent updates parameters using:\n\n\\[\n\\theta_{t+1} = \\theta_t - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta_t)\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(\\alpha\\) is the learning rate.\n\nNewton’s method updates parameters using:\n\n\\[\n\\theta_{t+1} = \\theta_t - H^{-1}\\nabla J(\\theta_t)\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\nabla J(\\theta_t)\\) is the gradient,\n- \\(H\\) is the Hessian matrix of second derivatives,\n- \\(H^{-1}\\) adjusts the step using curvature information.\n\nThe key difference is:\n\n**Gradient descent moves in the direction of the negative gradient, while Newton’s method uses both the gradient and the curvature of the function to choose a more informed step.**\n\nIntuitively, gradient descent asks: “Which direction goes downhill fastest?”\n\nNewton’s method asks: “Given the local slope and curvature, where does the function’s minimum seem to be?”\n\nBecause Newton’s method uses curvature, it can converge much faster near a minimum. However, computing and inverting the Hessian can be very expensive, especially for high-dimensional machine learning models. That is why gradient descent and its variants are more commonly used in large-scale machine learning.",
    "Gradient descent and simulated annealing are both optimization methods, but they are quite different in how they search for a minimum.\n\n| Aspect | Gradient Descent | Simulated Annealing |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type of method | First-order iterative optimization | Stochastic global optimization |\n| Uses gradients? | Yes | No |\n| Requires differentiability? | Yes, typically | No |\n| Search behavior | Moves downhill along the negative gradient | Randomly explores possible solutions |\n| Can accept worse solutions? | Usually no | Yes, especially early on |\n| Main control parameter | Learning rate | Temperature schedule |\n| Best suited for | Smooth differentiable functions | Rugged, discrete, or non-convex search spaces |\n| Risk | Can get stuck in local minima | Can escape local minima, but may be slower |\n\nGradient descent updates a point by moving in the direction of the negative gradient:\n\n\\[\n\\theta_{t+1} = \\theta_t - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta_t)\n\\]\n\nIt uses local slope information to decide where to go next.\n\nSimulated annealing, by contrast, randomly proposes a new solution. If the new solution is better, it accepts it. If the new solution is worse, it may still accept it with some probability. That probability decreases over time as the “temperature” is lowered.\n\nA typical acceptance probability for a worse move is:\n\n\\[\nP = e^{-\\Delta E / T}\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\Delta E\\) is how much worse the new solution is,\n- \\(T\\) is the temperature.\n\nThe key difference is:\n\n**Gradient descent follows the local downhill direction using gradients, while simulated annealing performs randomized search and can sometimes move uphill to escape local minima.**\n\nIntuitively:\n\n- Gradient descent is like walking downhill by feeling the slope under your feet.\n- Simulated annealing is like randomly trying nearby locations, sometimes accepting worse spots early on to avoid getting trapped, then becoming more selective over time."
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "Gradient descent is an optimization algorithm used to find the minimum of a function.\n\nIn machine learning, it is commonly used to reduce a model’s error or loss. The idea is:\n\n1. Start with some initial parameter values.\n2. Calculate the gradient, which tells you the direction of steepest increase of the function.\n3. Move in the opposite direction of the gradient, because you want to decrease the function.\n4. Repeat until the function value is low enough or stops improving much.\n\nMathematically, the update rule is often written as:\n\n\\[\n\\theta := \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\theta\\) represents the parameters being optimized\n- \\(J(\\theta)\\) is the loss or cost function\n- \\(\\nabla J(\\theta)\\) is the gradient of the loss\n- \\(\\alpha\\) is the learning rate, which controls the step size\n\nFor example, imagine standing on a hill in fog and trying to reach the lowest point. You feel the slope under your feet and take a small step downhill. Repeating this process is like gradient descent.\n\nCommon variants include:\n\n- Batch gradient descent: uses the whole dataset each step\n- Stochastic gradient descent: uses one training example at a time\n- Mini-batch gradient descent: uses a small batch of examples, common in deep learning\n\nThe learning rate is important: if it is too large, the algorithm may overshoot the minimum; if it is too small, training may be very slow.",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "Gradient descent and stochastic gradient descent differ mainly in **how much data they use to compute each update**.\n\n### 1. Gradient Descent / Batch Gradient Descent\n\nStandard gradient descent, often called **batch gradient descent**, computes the gradient using the **entire training dataset** before updating the model parameters.\n\nUpdate:\n\n\\[\n\\theta := \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere the gradient is calculated from all training examples.\n\n**Pros:**\n- More stable and smooth convergence\n- Each update points in a reliable downhill direction\n\n**Cons:**\n- Can be very slow for large datasets\n- Requires processing the full dataset for every update\n- Can be computationally expensive\n\n---\n\n### 2. Stochastic Gradient Descent, SGD\n\nSGD computes the gradient using **one randomly selected training example** at a time.\n\nUpdate for one example:\n\n\\[\n\\theta := \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J_i(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(J_i(\\theta)\\) is the loss for a single training example.\n\n**Pros:**\n- Much faster updates\n- Works well for large datasets\n- Can sometimes escape shallow local minima because of noisy updates\n\n**Cons:**\n- Updates are noisy and less stable\n- Loss may fluctuate rather than decrease smoothly\n- May require careful learning-rate tuning\n\n---\n\n### Simple comparison\n\n| Method | Data used per update | Speed per update | Stability |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Batch gradient descent | Entire dataset | Slow | Stable |\n| SGD | One example | Fast | Noisy |\n| Mini-batch gradient descent | Small batch | Balanced | Moderately stable |\n\nIn practice, when people say **SGD**, they often mean **mini-batch SGD**, where each update uses a small batch of examples, such as 32, 64, or 128 samples. This is the most common approach in deep learning.",
    "Gradient descent and Newton’s method are both optimization algorithms, but they differ in **what information they use** and **how they choose update steps**.\n\n## 1. Gradient descent uses first-order information\n\nGradient descent uses only the **gradient**, or first derivative, of the function.\n\nUpdate rule:\n\n\\[\n\\theta := \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\theta\\) are the parameters\n- \\(J(\\theta)\\) is the objective or loss function\n- \\(\\nabla J(\\theta)\\) is the gradient\n- \\(\\alpha\\) is the learning rate\n\nThe gradient tells you the direction of steepest increase, so gradient descent moves in the opposite direction.\n\n### Key idea\n\nGradient descent asks:\n\n> “Which direction is downhill?”\n\nIt does not directly use information about how curved the function is.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Newton’s method uses second-order information\n\nNewton’s method uses both the **gradient** and the **Hessian**, which is the matrix of second derivatives.\n\nUpdate rule:\n\n\\[\n\\theta := \\theta - H^{-1} \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\nabla J(\\theta)\\) is the gradient\n- \\(H\\) is the Hessian matrix\n- \\(H^{-1}\\) is the inverse of the Hessian\n\nThe Hessian describes the curvature of the function.\n\n### Key idea\n\nNewton’s method asks:\n\n> “Which direction is downhill, and how curved is the surface?”\n\nBecause it uses curvature, Newton’s method can take more informed steps.\n\n---\n\n## Main differences\n\n| Feature | Gradient Descent | Newton’s Method |\n|---|---|---|\n| Uses gradient? | Yes | Yes |\n| Uses Hessian? | No | Yes |\n| Type | First-order method | Second-order method |\n| Step size | Controlled by learning rate \\(\\alpha\\) | Determined by Hessian curvature |\n| Cost per iteration | Usually cheap | Often expensive |\n| Convergence | Usually slower | Often faster near optimum |\n| Common in deep learning? | Yes | Less common for large models |\n\n---\n\n## Example intuition\n\nImagine you are walking downhill in fog.\n\n**Gradient descent** tells you:\n\n> “Step downhill in this direction.”\n\nBut you have to choose how big a step to take.\n\n**Newton’s method** tells you:\n\n> “Step downhill, and also adjust your step based on how steeply the ground is curving.”\n\nSo Newton’s method can often reach the minimum in fewer steps.\n\n---\n\n## Why not always use Newton’s method?\n\nNewton’s method can be very powerful, but it has practical drawbacks.\n\nFor a model with \\(n\\) parameters, the Hessian is an \\(n \\times n\\) matrix. Computing and inverting it can be very expensive.\n\nFor large neural networks with millions or billions of parameters, storing and inverting the Hessian is usually impractical.\n\nThat is why gradient descent and variants like SGD, mini-batch SGD, Adam, and RMSProp are more common in large-scale machine learning.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nGradient descent uses only the slope of the loss function, while Newton’s method uses both the slope and the curvature.\n\nIn short:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Gradient descent: uses gradient}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\text{Newton's method: uses gradient + Hessian}\n\\]\n\nNewton’s method can converge faster, especially near the minimum, but each step is much more computationally expensive.",
    "Gradient descent and simulated annealing are both optimization methods, but they work very differently.\n\n## 1. Gradient descent uses gradients\n\nGradient descent uses the **gradient**, or slope, of the objective function to decide how to update the parameters.\n\nUpdate rule:\n\n\\[\n\\theta := \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\theta\\) are the parameters\n- \\(J(\\theta)\\) is the objective or loss function\n- \\(\\nabla J(\\theta)\\) is the gradient\n- \\(\\alpha\\) is the learning rate\n\nGradient descent moves in the direction that locally decreases the function fastest.\n\n### Key idea\n\nGradient descent asks:\n\n> “Which nearby direction goes downhill?”\n\nIt is a **local optimization method**.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Simulated annealing uses random exploration\n\nSimulated annealing does **not require gradients**. Instead, it randomly proposes new solutions and decides whether to accept them.\n\nIf a proposed solution is better, it is usually accepted.\n\nIf it is worse, it may still be accepted with some probability. That probability decreases over time as the “temperature” is lowered.\n\nA common acceptance rule is:\n\n\\[\nP(\\text{accept worse move}) = e^{-\\Delta E / T}\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\Delta E\\) is how much worse the new solution is\n- \\(T\\) is the temperature\n\nAt high temperature, the algorithm explores more freely. At low temperature, it becomes more conservative.\n\n### Key idea\n\nSimulated annealing asks:\n\n> “Should I try this random move, even if it is temporarily worse?”\n\nThis helps it escape local minima.\n\n---\n\n## Main differences\n\n| Feature | Gradient Descent | Simulated Annealing |\n|---|---|---|\n| Uses gradients? | Yes | No |\n| Search style | Moves downhill locally | Random exploration |\n| Can accept worse solutions? | Usually no | Yes |\n| Good for smooth differentiable functions? | Yes | Not required |\n| Handles discrete problems? | Not naturally | Yes |\n| Risk of local minima | Can get stuck | Better at escaping |\n| Speed | Often faster when gradients exist | Often slower |\n| Common in neural networks? | Very common | Less common |\n\n---\n\n## Intuition\n\nImagine trying to find the lowest point in a landscape.\n\n**Gradient descent** is like walking downhill by feeling the slope under your feet. You always try to move downward.\n\n**Simulated annealing** is like wandering around randomly. Early on, you are willing to climb uphill sometimes, because that might help you get over a hill and find a deeper valley elsewhere. Later, you become less willing to move uphill and settle into a good low point.\n\n---\n\n## When to use each\n\nUse **gradient descent** when:\n\n- The objective function is differentiable\n- Gradients are available or easy to compute\n- The problem is large-scale, such as training neural networks\n- You want efficient local optimization\n\nUse **simulated annealing** when:\n\n- The function is not differentiable\n- The search space is discrete or combinatorial\n- Gradients are unavailable\n- Escaping local minima is important\n\nExamples of simulated annealing use cases include scheduling, routing, layout optimization, and other combinatorial optimization problems.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nGradient descent follows the slope downhill using derivatives.\n\nSimulated annealing randomly explores the search space and can temporarily accept worse solutions to avoid getting stuck.\n\nIn short:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Gradient descent: gradient-based local search}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\text{Simulated annealing: random global search with cooling}\n\\]"
  ],
