        "user": "How does \"gradient descent\" differ from Newton's method?",
        "assistant": "Gradient descent and Newton’s method are both iterative optimization methods, but they differ mainly in the information they use to choose each step.\n\n| Aspect | Gradient Descent | Newton’s Method |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type of method | First-order optimization method | Second-order optimization method |\n| Uses gradient? | Yes | Yes |\n| Uses Hessian / curvature? | No | Yes |\n| Step direction | Negative gradient direction | Direction adjusted by curvature |\n| Step size | Controlled by learning rate | Often determined by Hessian; may still use damping/line search |\n| Computational cost | Usually cheaper per iteration | More expensive per iteration |\n| Convergence | Often slower, especially near optimum | Often faster near optimum |\n| Practicality in large ML models | Very common | Often too expensive for large models |\n\nGradient descent updates parameters using:\n\n\\[\n\\theta_{t+1} = \\theta_t - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta_t)\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(\\alpha\\) is the learning rate.\n\nNewton’s method updates parameters using:\n\n\\[\n\\theta_{t+1} = \\theta_t - H^{-1}\\nabla J(\\theta_t)\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\nabla J(\\theta_t)\\) is the gradient,\n- \\(H\\) is the Hessian matrix of second derivatives,\n- \\(H^{-1}\\) adjusts the step using curvature information.\n\nThe key difference is:\n\n**Gradient descent moves in the direction of the negative gradient, while Newton’s method uses both the gradient and the curvature of the function to choose a more informed step.**\n\nIntuitively, gradient descent asks: “Which direction goes downhill fastest?”\n\nNewton’s method asks: “Given the local slope and curvature, where does the function’s minimum seem to be?”\n\nBecause Newton’s method uses curvature, it can converge much faster near a minimum. However, computing and inverting the Hessian can be very expensive, especially for high-dimensional machine learning models. That is why gradient descent and its variants are more commonly used in large-scale machine learning.",
