      {
        "user": "How does \"gradient descent\" differ from simulated annealing?",
        "assistant": "Gradient descent and simulated annealing are both optimization methods, but they are quite different in how they search for a minimum.\n\n| Aspect | Gradient Descent | Simulated Annealing |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type of method | First-order iterative optimization | Stochastic global optimization |\n| Uses gradients? | Yes | No |\n| Requires differentiability? | Yes, typically | No |\n| Search behavior | Moves downhill along the negative gradient | Randomly explores possible solutions |\n| Can accept worse solutions? | Usually no | Yes, especially early on |\n| Main control parameter | Learning rate | Temperature schedule |\n| Best suited for | Smooth differentiable functions | Rugged, discrete, or non-convex search spaces |\n| Risk | Can get stuck in local minima | Can escape local minima, but may be slower |\n\nGradient descent updates a point by moving in the direction of the negative gradient:\n\n\\[\n\\theta_{t+1} = \\theta_t - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta_t)\n\\]\n\nIt uses local slope information to decide where to go next.\n\nSimulated annealing, by contrast, randomly proposes a new solution. If the new solution is better, it accepts it. If the new solution is worse, it may still accept it with some probability. That probability decreases over time as the “temperature” is lowered.\n\nA typical acceptance probability for a worse move is:\n\n\\[\nP = e^{-\\Delta E / T}\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\Delta E\\) is how much worse the new solution is,\n- \\(T\\) is the temperature.\n\nThe key difference is:\n\n**Gradient descent follows the local downhill direction using gradients, while simulated annealing performs randomized search and can sometimes move uphill to escape local minima.**\n\nIntuitively:\n\n- Gradient descent is like walking downhill by feeling the slope under your feet.\n- Simulated annealing is like randomly trying nearby locations, sometimes accepting worse spots early on to avoid getting trapped, then becoming more selective over time.",
