        "user": "How does \"gradient descent\" differ from stochastic gradient descent (SGD)?",
        "assistant": "Gradient descent and stochastic gradient descent differ mainly in **how much data they use to compute each update**.\n\n### 1. Gradient Descent / Batch Gradient Descent\n\nStandard gradient descent, often called **batch gradient descent**, computes the gradient using the **entire training dataset** before updating the model parameters.\n\nUpdate:\n\n\\[\n\\theta := \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere the gradient is calculated from all training examples.\n\n**Pros:**\n- More stable and smooth convergence\n- Each update points in a reliable downhill direction\n\n**Cons:**\n- Can be very slow for large datasets\n- Requires processing the full dataset for every update\n- Can be computationally expensive\n\n---\n\n### 2. Stochastic Gradient Descent, SGD\n\nSGD computes the gradient using **one randomly selected training example** at a time.\n\nUpdate for one example:\n\n\\[\n\\theta := \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J_i(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(J_i(\\theta)\\) is the loss for a single training example.\n\n**Pros:**\n- Much faster updates\n- Works well for large datasets\n- Can sometimes escape shallow local minima because of noisy updates\n\n**Cons:**\n- Updates are noisy and less stable\n- Loss may fluctuate rather than decrease smoothly\n- May require careful learning-rate tuning\n\n---\n\n### Simple comparison\n\n| Method | Data used per update | Speed per update | Stability |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Batch gradient descent | Entire dataset | Slow | Stable |\n| SGD | One example | Fast | Noisy |\n| Mini-batch gradient descent | Small batch | Balanced | Moderately stable |\n\nIn practice, when people say **SGD**, they often mean **mini-batch SGD**, where each update uses a small batch of examples, such as 32, 64, or 128 samples. This is the most common approach in deep learning.",
