      {
        "user": "How does \"gradient descent\" differ from simulated annealing?",
        "assistant": "Gradient descent and simulated annealing are both optimization methods, but they work very differently.\n\n## 1. Gradient descent uses gradients\n\nGradient descent uses the **gradient**, or slope, of the objective function to decide how to update the parameters.\n\nUpdate rule:\n\n\\[\n\\theta := \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\theta\\) are the parameters\n- \\(J(\\theta)\\) is the objective or loss function\n- \\(\\nabla J(\\theta)\\) is the gradient\n- \\(\\alpha\\) is the learning rate\n\nGradient descent moves in the direction that locally decreases the function fastest.\n\n### Key idea\n\nGradient descent asks:\n\n> “Which nearby direction goes downhill?”\n\nIt is a **local optimization method**.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Simulated annealing uses random exploration\n\nSimulated annealing does **not require gradients**. Instead, it randomly proposes new solutions and decides whether to accept them.\n\nIf a proposed solution is better, it is usually accepted.\n\nIf it is worse, it may still be accepted with some probability. That probability decreases over time as the “temperature” is lowered.\n\nA common acceptance rule is:\n\n\\[\nP(\\text{accept worse move}) = e^{-\\Delta E / T}\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\(\\Delta E\\) is how much worse the new solution is\n- \\(T\\) is the temperature\n\nAt high temperature, the algorithm explores more freely. At low temperature, it becomes more conservative.\n\n### Key idea\n\nSimulated annealing asks:\n\n> “Should I try this random move, even if it is temporarily worse?”\n\nThis helps it escape local minima.\n\n---\n\n## Main differences\n\n| Feature | Gradient Descent | Simulated Annealing |\n|---|---|---|\n| Uses gradients? | Yes | No |\n| Search style | Moves downhill locally | Random exploration |\n| Can accept worse solutions? | Usually no | Yes |\n| Good for smooth differentiable functions? | Yes | Not required |\n| Handles discrete problems? | Not naturally | Yes |\n| Risk of local minima | Can get stuck | Better at escaping |\n| Speed | Often faster when gradients exist | Often slower |\n| Common in neural networks? | Very common | Less common |\n\n---\n\n## Intuition\n\nImagine trying to find the lowest point in a landscape.\n\n**Gradient descent** is like walking downhill by feeling the slope under your feet. You always try to move downward.\n\n**Simulated annealing** is like wandering around randomly. Early on, you are willing to climb uphill sometimes, because that might help you get over a hill and find a deeper valley elsewhere. Later, you become less willing to move uphill and settle into a good low point.\n\n---\n\n## When to use each\n\nUse **gradient descent** when:\n\n- The objective function is differentiable\n- Gradients are available or easy to compute\n- The problem is large-scale, such as training neural networks\n- You want efficient local optimization\n\nUse **simulated annealing** when:\n\n- The function is not differentiable\n- The search space is discrete or combinatorial\n- Gradients are unavailable\n- Escaping local minima is important\n\nExamples of simulated annealing use cases include scheduling, routing, layout optimization, and other combinatorial optimization problems.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nGradient descent follows the slope downhill using derivatives.\n\nSimulated annealing randomly explores the search space and can temporarily accept worse solutions to avoid getting stuck.\n\nIn short:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Gradient descent: gradient-based local search}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\text{Simulated annealing: random global search with cooling}\n\\]",
